The Jaguar E-type lies amongst the automotive legends. Its gorgeous design, technological innovation, and racing achievement is unprecedented. First introduced in March of 1961 at the Geneva Auto Salon, the E-Type captured the hearts and minds of the entire automotive community. As oft quoted, Enzo Ferrari would even say it was “the most beautiful car ever made.” After nearly 60 years, Jaguar’s E-Type remains one of the most dramatic automobiles in the world.

The E-Type’s 14-year production run evolved over three major iterations. The extremely desirable first series lasted from 1961–1967. The second series E-Types were produced between 1967–1971, while the V-12–powered third series cars were produced from 1971 until 1975. While 1961–1967 E-Types retain the Series 1 designation, a number of improvements were made for the later cars. First and foremost, engine size was enlarged to 4.2 liters, increasing the engine’s output to a then powerful 265 hp and 273 foot-pounds of torque. The larger engine also featured a fully synchronized four-speed manual transmission, resulting in one of the finest driving sports cars ever produced.

This beautiful Series 1 4.2-Litre Roadster is an exceptional example of the model. It was originally finished in Carmen Red over a black interior with a black convertible top. Its accompanying Jaguar Heritage Trust Certificate also records the E-Type as being dispatched on 11 November 1966 and then delivered through Jaguar Cars in New York. The original owner is noted as Roland M. Scott. While little is known of its intervening history, the car was owned for an extended period by Thomas Whiteside of North Attleborough Massachusetts before it was subsequently acquired by the current owner, still finished in its original color.

Looking for an exceptional example to restore, the consignor sent the E-Type to marque expert Dave Ferguson in Campbell, California. Dave Ferguson, a Jaguar Association chief judge, executed the 18-month, nut-and-bolt rotisserie restoration starting in September of 2012, finishing in December 2013. Finished in beautiful and period-appropriate Cotswold Blue over a red interior, the thoroughly documented restoration incorporates several subtle upgrades in an effort to improve drivability, including a 3.07 rear-end for highway driving, Dynamat sound and heat insulation, an aluminum radiator with a 12-blade cooling fan, a lightened flywheel, and sport camshafts. Furthermore, the car features a full set of tools, jack, and spare wheel as well as an owner’s manual, service manual, and period documentation.

This particular example will not fail to impress, as it did when it placed 2nd in class at the 2014 Hillsborough Concours d’Elegance. description: 1967 JAGUAR E-TYPE 4.2 LITER SERIES 1 ROADSTER

--Racing Green with Tan leather interior, Tan carpeting, Black everflex top, 27,000 original miles from new, Sympathetically restored, Triple S.U. carb 4.2 liter engine, 4-speed transmission, Numbers matching.

This E-Type has been delivered to its original owner on Mr. P. Martin on February 27th, 1967 and is a late Series 1 car, often referred to as a Series 1.25 as the serial number is before the Series 1.5 cars, which had notable differences. These rare late Series 1 cars feature headlights retaining the covered lens bucket contours and the desirable triple SU carburetors, maintaining the original and impressive 265hp and Salisbury limited slip differential.
This Roadster is believed to be an original 27,000 miles example. Early history is unknown, but the chassis and body unequivocally acknowledge this.

As a result of originality and a devoted maintenance regimen, it is one of the nicest, tightest, straightest and most honest E-type's we have seen. Purchased in 1997 in restored form by its current owner-collector, a well-known client to Autosport Designs Inc., this XK-E has been well-cared for and was (circa 1990's) sympathetically restored by well-known Jaguar specialist, Ed Miller in Stormville, NY. A large binder accompanies the car and details ownership and fastidious service/maintenance history back to the mid-1990's.

During current ownership, this E-type has received annual as-needed service, maintenance and upgrades to maintain its superb, ready to use condition. Within the past two years, a complete new interior in stunning tan leather was executed with the finest craftsmanship and materials throughout. In addition, the complete braking system has been refurbished, all fluids and filters refreshed and all regular maintenance has kept this example in absolutely excellent driving order.

A recent road test attests to the car performing flawlessly in every way, and it is indeed ready for immediate use and enjoyment. This E-type is complete with owner records as well as factory tools, hammer, jack and Heritage Certificate.

Presented here at Cooper Classics is this stunning 1967 Jaguar XKE Series I Convertible finished in a very elegant color scheme of Dark Opalescent Blue over a grey leather interior. The previous owner founded both Jag Atlanta, which was the biggest supplier of E-Type parts in the Southern United States, and Jaguar Performance Center Inc., a restoration facility that restored this car. This E-Type is from his personal collection and he put less than 1,000 miles on the car after completing the restoration in the late 90s. He considered this his personal XKE and because of his care, the car has stood up exceptionally well. Even though this was a nut and bolt restoration the car was in such excellent condition that some of the original cosmetic interior was saved to create character and patina. When Cooper Classics received the car we upgraded and refreshed the restoration to make it more current with new chrome, lights and engine detailing. Upgrades include a Stayfast convertible top and an Ansa exhaust system. The car retains its original 4.2 litre engine producing 268 horsepower and 283 lb/ft of torque and its original full synchromesh gearbox. This E-Type has been taken care of by a Jaguar expert since his ownership in 1975 and took home a Jaguar Club of North America Best in Class win when it was shown in the 90s. The original wooden is not currently fitted to the car but is in excellent condition and comes with the car. The car also comes with its original tool roll, jack, owners manual, documents, Smith clock and Grease gun instructions and rare front passenger side foot rest.

description: This original 1967 Series 1 Jaguar XKE is a Jaguar Daimler Heritage Car with complete matching numbers and only 58,435 original miles. When the Jaguar E-Type was introduced to the world in the early 1960s, Enzo Ferrari described its design as the “most beautiful car ever made.” Its combination of exquisite styling and high performance made the E-Type Jaguar Series 1 one of the most collectable automobiles of all time. This particular Series 1 is a transitional car that rolled off the lot on May 4, 1967 and was one of the first cars not to have covered headlights. With its Old English White exterior (repainted only once 30 years ago) and sleek black leather interior, this Jaguar could make quite the statement. As part of the collection of a meticulous collector of European automobiles, this vehicle comes with all of its original owner's manuals, full documentation of service, and a documented record of all prior owners.

Under the hood, this E-Type sports a 4.2L twin-cam straight-six engine that was rebuilt 8,000 miles ago with three SU carburetors and a 4-speed transmission with a new clutch, throw out bearing and clutch slave cylinder. The front suspension bushings have been recently replaced and the brakes rebuilt, and the original radiator has an upgraded fan motor. In addition, the front wiring harness has been replaced with a concours-quality harness, and the carburetors were rebuilt a few years ago. The sale includes the Jaguar's original tool kit and new Coker radial tires. According to the consignor, the vehicle is in overall very good condition and needs nothing. Sold with a title and registration.
